{"title_page": "Kristen Bell", "text_new": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Use American English|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Kristen Bell\n| image        = Kristen Bell Paris Fashion Week Spring Summer 2020 (cropped).jpg\n| caption      = Bell at [[Paris Fashion Week]] in 2019\n| birth_name   = Kristen Anne Bell\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1980|7|18}}\n| birth_place  = [[Huntington Woods, Michigan]], U.S.\n| residence    = [[Los Angeles, California]], U.S.\n| alma_mater   = [[New York University]]\n| occupation   = Actress, singer, voice actress, director <!--Please do not add to this list without first discussing your proposal on the talk page. -->\n| years_active = 1992\u2013present\n| spouse       = {{Marriage|[[Dax Shepard]]|2013}}\n| children     = 2\n}}\n'''Kristen Anne Bell''' (born July 18, 1980)<ref name=peoplebio>{{cite web|url= http://www.people.com/people/kristen_bell/biography/ |title=Kristen Bell |work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |accessdate=June 26, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130602170549/http://www.people.com/people/kristen_bell/biography |archivedate=June 2, 2013 }}</ref> is an American actress, singer, voice actress, and director. She began her professional acting career by starring in stage productions while attending the [[Tisch School of the Arts]] at [[New York University]]. In 2001, she made her [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] debut as [[Becky Thatcher]] in the comedy musical ''[[The Adventures of Tom Sawyer (musical)|The Adventures of Tom Sawyer]]'' and appeared in a Broadway revival of ''[[The Crucible]]'' the following year. In 2004, she appeared in the action thriller film ''[[Spartan (film)|Spartan]]'' and received critical praise for her performance in the television drama film ''[[Gracie's Choice]]''.\n\nBell garnered critical acclaim for her first major role as the [[Veronica Mars (character)|title character]] in the teen [[Noir fiction|noir]] drama television series ''[[Veronica Mars]]'' (2004\u20132007). For her performance, she was awarded a [[Saturn Award for Best Actress on Television]]. She reprised the [[eponym]]ous role in the [[Veronica Mars (film)|2014 film continuation]] and the [[Veronica Mars (season 4)|2019 revival series]]. During her time on ''Veronica Mars'', Bell starred as Mary Lane in the musical film ''[[Reefer Madness: The Movie Musical]]'' (2005), a reprise of the role she had played in the New York [[Reefer Madness (musical)|musical upon which the film was based]]. From 2007 to 2008, Bell starred as [[Elle Bishop]] in the [[science fiction]] drama series ''[[Heroes (U.S. TV series)|Heroes]]''. From 2007 to 2012, she voiced the titular narrator in the teen drama series ''[[Gossip Girl]]''.\n\nIn 2008, she had her breakout film role as the title character in ''[[Forgetting Sarah Marshall]]''. She has since appeared in a number of comedy films, including ''[[Couples Retreat]]'' (2009), ''[[When in Rome (2010 film)|When in Rome]]'' (2010), ''[[You Again]]'' (2010), ''[[The Boss (2016 film)|The Boss]]'' (2016), ''[[Bad Moms]]'' (2016), and ''[[A Bad Moms Christmas]]'' (2017). Bell garnered further recognition for voicing [[Anna (Frozen)|Princess Anna]] in the Disney animated fantasy films ''[[Frozen (2013 film)|Frozen]]'' (2013), ''[[Ralph Breaks the Internet]]'' (2018), and ''[[Frozen II]]'' (2019), and the short films ''[[Frozen Fever]]'' (2015) and ''[[Olaf's Frozen Adventure]]'' (2017).\n\nFrom 2012 to 2016, Bell starred as Jeannie van der Hooven, the female lead on the [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] comedy series ''[[House of Lies]]''. From 2016 to 2020, she starred in the lead role of Eleanor Shellstrop on the acclaimed [[NBC]] comedy series ''[[The Good Place]]'', for which she received a [[Golden Globe Award]] nomination for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Television Series Musical or Comedy|Best Actress \u2013 Television Series Musical or Comedy]].\n\n==Early life and family==\nBell was born on July 18, 1980, in [[Huntington Woods, Michigan]], a suburb of [[Detroit]], where she was raised. Her mother, Lorelei (''n\u00e9e'' Frygier), is a [[registered nurse]], and her father, Tom Bell, works as a [[News broadcasting|television news]] director in Las Vegas, Nevada.<ref name=peoplebio/><ref name=CBSSacramento-Father-Irma-2017>{{cite news |last1=McClary |first1=Marianne |last2=Lopez |first2=Tony |last3=Bell |first3=Kristen |title=Actress Kristen Bell Reaching Out to Help Those Affected by Hurricane Irma |url=http://sacramento.cbslocal.com/2017/09/10/kristen-bell-hurricane-irma/ |work=[[KOVR|CBS Sacramento]] |date=September 10, 2017  |format=Includes video interview}}</ref> Her parents divorced when she was two years old, and she has two stepsisters from her father's second marriage. She also has two half-sisters and two half-brothers from her mother's second marriage.{{citation needed|date=June 2019}} Her mother is of [[Polish American|Polish]] descent, and her father has [[German American|German]], [[Scottish Americans|Scottish]] and [[Irish Americans|Irish]] ancestry.<ref>Stated on ''[[The Tonight Show with Jay Leno]]'', September 18, 2008</ref>\n\nBell stated that she did not like her first name at the age of four. Bell's mother convinced her to go by her middle name, Anne, instead; she used the name Annie until high school.<ref name=\"Ask\">{{cite web |title=Kristen Bell |publisher=[[Ask Men]] |url=http://www.askmen.com/celebs/women/actress_250/298_kristen_bell.html |accessdate=January 2, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080823031614/http://www.askmen.com/celebs/women/actress_250/298_kristen_bell.html |archivedate=August 23, 2008  }}</ref> Bell once broke both her wrists at the same time playing [[street hockey]] with friends.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/kristen-bell-has-a-stanley-cup-fantasy/ |title=Kristen Bell Has a Stanley Cup Fantasy |publisher=[[CBS News]] |date=May 28, 2008 |accessdate=October 17, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160109211056/http://www.cbsnews.com/news/kristen-bell-has-a-stanley-cup-fantasy/ |archivedate=January 9, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nJust before her freshman year of high school, Bell's parents decided to remove her from the [[state school|public school]] system.<ref name=\"Mars\">{{cite news| last= Hatty| first= Michele| title= She came from Mars| publisher= [[USA Weekend]]| date= February 26, 2006|url= http://www.usaweekend.com/06_issues/060226/060226kristen_bell.html|accessdate= January 4, 2008}} {{dead link| date=June 2010 | bot=DASHBot}}</ref> She attended [[Shrine Catholic High School]] in nearby [[Royal Oak, Michigan|Royal Oak]], where she took part in the drama and music club.<ref>{{cite interview\n |last=Bell\n |first=Kristen\n |interviewer=Molly Lopez\n |title=Veronica Mars' Kristen Bell\n |work=[[People (magazine)|People]]\n |date=April 22, 2005\n |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,1051629,00.html\n |accessdate=January 4, 2008\n |url-status=live\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080207015531/http://www.people.com/people/article/0%2C%2C1051629%2C00.html\n |archivedate=February 7, 2008\n}}</ref> During her time at the school, she won the starring role in the school's 1997 production of ''[[The Wonderful Wizard of Oz|The Wizard of Oz]]'', as [[Dorothy Gale]], and also appeared in productions of ''[[Fiddler on the Roof]]'' (1995), ''[[Lady, Be Good (musical)|Lady, Be Good]]'' (1996), and ''[[Li'l Abner (musical)|Li'l Abner]]'' (1998). In 1998, the year she graduated, Bell was named the yearbook's \"Best Looking Girl\" by senior class vote.<ref name=\"Saturday\">{{cite interview|last=Bell |first=Kristen |interviewer=Elijah Bates |title=Veronica Mars' star Kristen Bell |work=[[Saturday Night Magazine (US)|Saturday Night Magazine]] |date=April 25, 2007 |url=http://www.snmag.com/pdf/INTERVIEWS/Celebrity-Interviews/Kristen-Bell.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=January 4, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081218123920/http://www.snmag.com/pdf/INTERVIEWS/Celebrity-Interviews/Kristen-Bell.pdf |archivedate=December 18, 2008 |df= }}</ref>\n\nShortly after her high school graduation, Bell moved to New York City to attend [[New York University]]'s [[Tisch School of the Arts]],<ref name=\"Ask\"/> majoring in musical theater.<ref>{{cite web |title=Personality & Talent |publisher=[[Ask Men]] |url=http://www.askmen.com/celebs/women/actress_250/298_kristen_bell.html |accessdate=January 2, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080823031614/http://www.askmen.com/celebs/women/actress_250/298_kristen_bell.html |archivedate=August 23, 2008  }}</ref> In 2001, during her senior year, Bell left a few credits shy of graduating<ref name=\"Tough\"/> to take a role in the Broadway musical version of ''The Adventures of Tom Sawyer''.\n\n==Career==\n\n===1992\u20132003: Early work===\nIn 1992, Bell went to her first audition and won a dual role as a banana and a tree<ref name=\"Star\"/> in a suburban Detroit theater's production of ''[[Raggedy Ann and Andy]]''.<ref name=\"Ask\"/> Her mother had established her with an agent before Bell was 13, which allowed her to appear in newspaper advertisements for several Detroit retailers and television commercials. She also began private acting lessons.<ref name=\"Ask\"/> In 1998, she appeared with an uncredited role in the locally filmed movie ''[[Polish Wedding]]''.\n\nIn 2001, Bell left New York University to play a role as [[List of Tom Sawyer characters#Becky Thatcher|Becky Thatcher]] in the short-lived Broadway musical of ''[[The Adventures of Tom Sawyer (musical)|The Adventures of Tom Sawyer]]''. That same year, she made her credited film debut in ''[[Pootie Tang]]''. Her one line in the film was cut, and her appearance exists only as a scene shown during the credit sequence.<ref name=\"UGO\">{{cite interview|last=Bell |first=Kristen |interviewer=Daniel Robert Epstein |title=Kristen Bell of Veronica Mars (UPN) |work=[[UGO]] |year=2005 |url=http://www.ugo.com/channels/girlfriends/features/kristenbell/interview.asp |accessdate=January 3, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071223164122/http://www.ugo.com/channels/girlfriends/features/kristenbell/interview.asp |archivedate=December 23, 2007 |df= }}</ref> Additionally, she auditioned for the television series ''[[Smallville]]'' for the role of [[Chloe Sullivan]], which was eventually won by [[Allison Mack]].<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Holland |first=Richard |title=Veronica Mars: Series Finale |magazine=[[Pop Matters]] |date=May 27, 2007 |url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/41693/veronica-mars2/ |accessdate=January 2, 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080829190518/http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/41693/veronica-mars2/ |archivedate=August 29, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, she appeared in the Broadway revival of ''[[The Crucible]]'' with [[Liam Neeson]], [[Angela Bettis]] and [[Laura Linney]]. Bell then moved to Los Angeles in 2002 because of her friendship with writers [[Kevin Murphy (screenwriter)|Kevin Murphy]] and Dan Studney,<ref name=\"UGO\" /> and appeared in a handful of television shows as a special guest, finding trouble gaining a recurring role in a television series. Bell said she \"tested like eight times and booked nothing and every show [she] tested for got picked up\", including auditions for ''[[Skin (TV series)|Skin]]'' and a [[Norm Macdonald]] series.<ref name=\"Star\">{{cite web|title=Kristen Bell's star quality is no mystery on UPN |website=Pittsburghlive.com |date=November 23, 2004 |url=http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/s_275788.html |accessdate=January 4, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080124020416/http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/s_275788.html |archivedate=January 24, 2008  }}</ref>\n\n===2004\u20132006: ''Veronica Mars'' and other roles===\nIn 2004, Bell appeared in the [[Lifetime (TV network)|Lifetime]] television film ''[[Gracie's Choice]]'', which received one of the network's highest ratings.<ref name=\"Tough\">{{cite web|last=Nguyen |first=Lan N.|title=Kristen Bell's a Tough Act to Follow |website=Ivillage.com |year=2004 |url=http://entertainment.ivillage.com/features/0,,73r3smcc-p,00.html |accessdate=January 4, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080408152604/http://entertainment.ivillage.com/features/0%2C%2C73r3smcc-p%2C00.html |archivedate=April 8, 2008 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> She made her debut in a theatrically released film with [[David Mamet]]'s ''[[Spartan (film)|Spartan]]'', as Laura Newton, the kidnapped daughter of the U.S. President, acting alongside [[Val Kilmer]]. Bell also guest-starred on the [[HBO]] drama ''[[Deadwood (TV series)|Deadwood]]'' in a two-episode story arc (\"[[Bullock Returns to the Camp (Deadwood episode)|Bullock Returns to the Camp]]\" and \"[[Suffer the Little Children (Deadwood episode)|Suffer the Little Children]]\").\n\n[[File:Kristen Bell as Veronica Mars 2.jpg|alt=Head and shoulders shot of wide-eyed, young blond woman smiling into the camera.|thumb|Bell on the set of ''Veronica Mars'' in 2004]]\nAt 24, she won the role of the title character in [[UPN]]'s drama ''[[Veronica Mars]]'', which was launched in the fall of 2004. Created by [[Rob Thomas (writer)|Rob Thomas]], the series starred Bell as the seventeen-year-old anti-establishment high school student/detective. Bell drew on the parallels between the character of Veronica and her own life, since Bell's parents had divorced and her best friend had also died.<ref name=\"Tough\"/> The series earned acclaim from television critics, as did Bell's performance. Some critics asserted that her performance was overlooked, and deserved consideration for an [[Emmy Award]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Ellis |first=Rick |title=Predictions: 58th Annual Emmy Awards |publisher=[[KTVU]] |date=August 26, 2006 |url=http://www.ktvu.com/entertainment/9731047/detail.html |accessdate=January 3, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080125104302/http://www.ktvu.com/entertainment/9731047/detail.html |archivedate=January 25, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Goodman |first=Tim |title=As Emmys loom, it's time to accept that rage is futile |work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |date=September 15, 2005 |url=http://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/As-Emmys-loom-it-s-time-to-accept-that-rage-is-2569271.php |accessdate=January 3, 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120725030541/http://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/As-Emmys-loom-it-s-time-to-accept-that-rage-is-2569271.php |archivedate=July 25, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Beaumont |first=Chris |title=Emmy 2007: Down and Dirty Predictions |website=Blogcritics.org |date=September 16, 2007 |url=http://blogcritics.org/archives/2007/09/16/132139.php |accessdate=January 3, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080125162043/http://blogcritics.org/archives/2007/09/16/132139.php |archivedate=January 25, 2008 |df= }}</ref>\n\nAside from working on ''Veronica Mars'', Bell starred in ''[[Reefer Madness: The Movie Musical]]'', reprising the role she played in the short-lived 2001 [[Off-Broadway]] musical. The musical was a spoof of the [[Reefer Madness|1936 exploitation film of the same name]]. ''Reefer Madness: The Movie Musical'' debuted on the [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] network on April 16, 2005. Also in April, Bell starred as Gracie in ''[[Fifty Pills]]'', an entry for the [[Tribeca Film Festival]]. She appeared in a short independent film called ''The Receipt'' and the horror film ''Roman'', which was directed by her ''Crucible'' co-star Angela Bettis. Released on August 11, 2006, ''[[Pulse (2006 film)|Pulse]]'' starred Bell as the lead Mattie. A remake of the Japanese horror film ''[[Pulse (2001 film)|Kairo]]'', the film grossed US$27.9 million worldwide<ref>{{cite web|title=Pulse (2006) |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=pulse.htm |accessdate=January 2, 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930220824/http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=pulse.htm |archivedate=September 30, 2007 }}</ref> but garnered negative response from critics. Frank Scheck of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' commented, \"despite the starring presence of Kristen Bell, [the] young actress has far less interesting material to work with here than she does as [the character] 'Veronica Mars.'\"<ref name=\"Pulse\">{{cite news|last=Scheck |first=Frank |title=Pulse |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=August 14, 2006 |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/search/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1002985784 |accessdate=January 17, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012113515/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/search/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1002985784 |archivedate=October 12, 2007 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\n===2007\u20132011: Film breakthrough===\n''Veronica Mars'' continued on UPN for a second season; for the third season, the show was renewed and appeared on the newly created [[The CW]]. On January 19, 2007, CW Entertainment President [[Dawn Ostroff]] announced that while she was pleased with the gradual improvement of ''Veronica Mars's'' ratings, the series would be put on hiatus after February sweeps to air a new reality series, ''[[Pussycat Dolls Present: The Search for the Next Doll|Pussycat Dolls Present]]''. On May 17, 2007, Ostroff announced the cancellation of the series.<ref name=\"Finale\">{{cite news|title=2007 Cancelled Shows: CW Drops Old Favorites |website=Tvseriesfinale.com |date=May 17, 2007 |url=http://tvseriesfinale.com/articles/2007-cancelled-shows-cw-drops-old-favorites/ |accessdate=January 2, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20080908045451/http://tvseriesfinale.com/articles/2007-cancelled-shows-cw-drops-old-favorites/ |archivedate=September 8, 2008 |df= }}</ref> A two-hour series finale aired in the United States on May 22, 2007, and on June 11, 2007, Thomas officially announced in an email to ''[[TV Guide]]'s'' Michael Ausiello that ''Veronica Mars'' had been canceled by the CW.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ausiello |first=Michael |title=Veronica Mars is Now \"Officially Dead\" |work=[[TV Guide]] |date=June 11, 2007 |url=http://community.tvguide.com/blog-entry/TVGuide-Editors-Blog/Ausiello-Report/Veronica-Mars-Officially/800016822 |accessdate=January 2, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080208081306/http://community.tvguide.com/blog-entry/TVGuide-Editors-Blog/Ausiello-Report/Veronica-Mars-Officially/800016822 |archivedate=February 8, 2008 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> A ''Veronica Mars'' feature film and comic book series continuation had been discussed,<ref>{{cite news|title='Veronica Mars' Eyes Comics, Movie |website=Zap2it.com |date=June 13, 2007 |url=http://www.zap2it.com/tv/news/zap-veronicamarscomicsmoviepossibility,0,1929984.story |accessdate=January 2, 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080105035054/http://www.zap2it.com/tv/news/zap-veronicamarscomicsmoviepossibility%2C0%2C1929984.story |archivedate=January 5, 2008 }}</ref> and for a short time there was talk of another collaboration between Bell and creator Thomas that would be unrelated to the ''Veronica Mars'' series.<ref name=\"Finale\"/>\n\nFollowing the cancellation of ''Veronica Mars'', Bell voiced interest in appearing on ''Heroes'' because she was a fan.<ref name=\"scifi\">{{cite interview| subject= Bell, Kristen| subject2= Kring, Tim| interviewer= Renee Burl| title= Tim Kring & Kristen Bell interview| website=Thescifiworld.net| date= October 26, 2007| url= http://www.thescifiworld.net/interviews/tim_kring_kristen_bell_01.htm| accessdate= November 26, 2007}}</ref> On July 29, 2007, during a train ride back to Los Angeles from the [[San Diego Comic-Con]] with ''Heroes'' actors [[Zachary Quinto]] and [[Masi Oka]], and writers from the series, the writers had mentioned that if she \"ever want[ed] to come on ''Heroes'', give us [writers] a call,\" to which Bell said she would \"love to.\"<ref name=\"TV guide\">{{cite interview|subject=Bell, Kristen |interviewer=Michael Ausiello |title=Exclusive: Kristen Bell's First Interview Since Becoming a Hero! |work=[[TV Guide]] |date=August 20, 2007 |url=http://community.tvguide.com/blog-entry/TVGuide-Editors-Blog/Ausiello-Report/Exclusive-Kristen-Bell/800020731 |accessdate=November 25, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071112184315/http://community.tvguide.com/blog-entry/TVGuide-Editors-Blog/Ausiello-Report/Exclusive-Kristen-Bell/800020731 |archivedate=November 12, 2007 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> Meanwhile, there were discussions about a role on ''[[Lost (TV series)|Lost]]'', but Bell turned down the role<ref name=\"EWVid\">Jensen, Jeff, [[Damon Lindelof|Lindelof, Damon]] & [[Carlton Cuse|Cuse, Carlton]], \"[http://www.ew.com/ew/package/0,,1550612_20245764,00.html?bcpid=4396297001&bclid=4370457001&bctid=8633832001 'Lost' producers&nbsp;\u2013 5] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161230000655/http://ew.com/ew/package/0%2C%2C1550612_20245764%2C00.html/?bcpid=4396297001&bclid=4370457001&bctid=8633832001 |date=December 30, 2016 }}\", ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''. Retrieved April 11, 2009.</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Kubicek |first=John |title='Heroes' Exclusive: Kristen Bell and Tim Kring Reveal Season 2 Spoilers |website=Buddytv.com |date=October 16, 2007 |url=http://www.buddytv.com/articles/heroes/heroes-exclusive-kristen-bell-12506.aspx |accessdate=January 4, 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150713012044/http://www.buddytv.com/articles/heroes/heroes-exclusive-kristen-bell-12506.aspx |archivedate=July 13, 2015 }}</ref> of [[Charlotte Staples Lewis]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Goldman |first=Eric |title=Kristen Bell to Join Lost? |website=IGN |date=August 8, 2007 |url=http://tv.ign.com/articles/811/811463p1.html |accessdate=January 4, 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081216081645/http://tv.ign.com/articles/811/811463p1.html |archivedate=December 16, 2008 }}</ref> Bell portrayed [[Elle Bishop]] on ''Heroes'', a \"mysterious young lady\" with an \"awesome power\".<ref name=\"TV guide\"/> She did not have to audition for the role of Elle,<ref name=\"UGO\"/> who made her first appearance in an October 2007 episode, and appeared in twelve episodes during the run of the series.<ref name=\"Variety\">{{cite news| last= Adalian| first= Josef| title= Kristen Bell throws curve to 'Heroes'| work= [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]| date= August 19, 2007| url= http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117970491.html?categoryid=14&cs=1&query=kristen+bell| accessdate= November 25, 2007}}</ref> The casting of Bell, ''Heroes'' creator [[Tim Kring]] explained, \"was not easy to pull off\", but because of the large ensemble cast of the series and multiple [[story arc]]s, \"we found a way to jump into a small window in [Bell's] schedule.\"<ref name=\"Variety\"/> Bell lent her voice to the CW series ''[[Gossip Girl]]'': she voiced the title character in every episode of the series, appearing in person only for a surprise cameo in the final episode, portraying herself.\n\n[[File:Kristen Bell at the 2008 Tribeca Film Festival.JPG|alt=Head and shoulders of young, blond woman with hair curling below her shoulders, smiling.|thumb|upright|Bell at the 2008 [[Tribeca Film Festival]]]]\nShortly after the cancellation of ''Veronica Mars'' in early 2007, Bell filmed on location in [[Hawaii]] for a starring role as the title character in the [[Judd Apatow]] comedy ''[[Forgetting Sarah Marshall]]''. She regarded the [[improvisational comedy]] in the film as \"a lovely experience\".<ref name=\"UGO\" /> The film, written by and also starring [[Jason Segel]], was released theatrically on April 18, 2008, and greatly increased Bell's profile. Bell lent her voice and likeness to the video game ''[[Assassin's Creed (video game)|Assassin's Creed]]'', which was released on November 13, 2007, for the [[PlayStation 3]] and [[Xbox 360]] and April 8, 2008, for the [[Personal computer|PC]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Surette |first=Tim |title=Assassin's Creed stalks Kristen Bell |website=[[GameSpot]] |date=November 6, 2007 |url=http://www.gamespot.com/news/6182388.html |accessdate=January 2, 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081206182557/http://www.gamespot.com/news/6182388.html |archivedate=December 6, 2008 }}</ref> Bell reprised her role of Lucy in ''[[Assassin's Creed II]]'' released on November 17, 2009, and again in ''[[Assassin's Creed: Brotherhood]]'', released on November 16, 2010.<ref>{{cite news|title=Trailer, shots reveal actress Kristen Bell |publisher=[[ActionTrip]] |date=October 2, 2009 |url=http://www.actiontrip.com/rei/comments_news.phtml?id=100209_2 |accessdate=October 2, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091005070351/http://www.actiontrip.com/rei/comments_news.phtml?id=100209_2 |archivedate=October 5, 2009 |df= }}</ref> In the spring of 2006, she finished filming the ''[[Star Wars]]''-themed comedy ''[[Fanboys (film)|Fanboys]]''. Director [[Kyle Newman]] received additional funding to shoot new scenes, but the busy schedules of the actors only allowed for filming in September 2007. As a result, the release was delayed until January 14, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fanboys Pushed Back to January 2008 |website=Theforce.net |url=http://www.theforce.net/latestnews/story/Fanboys_Pushed_Back_To_January_2008_105913.asp |accessdate=October 5, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071005003049/http://www.theforce.net/latestnews/story/Fanboys_Pushed_Back_To_January_2008_105913.asp |archivedate=October 5, 2007 |df= }}</ref> Bell also starred in the 2009 comedies ''[[Serious Moonlight (2009 film)|Serious Moonlight]]'', alongside [[Meg Ryan]], and ''[[Couples Retreat]]'', which chronicles four couples who partake in therapy sessions at a tropical island resort. [[Jason Bateman]] played her husband.<ref>[http://movies.tvguide.com/Movie-News/Kristen-Bell-Kristin-26563.aspx Trio of Ladies Going on ''Couples Retreat''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081017103625/http://movies.tvguide.com/Movie-News/Kristen-Bell-Kristin-26563.aspx |date=October 17, 2008 }}\" ''[[TV Guide]]''. October 15, 2008. Retrieved October 15, 2008.</ref> She also provided the voice for Cora in ''[[Astro Boy (film)|Astro Boy]]''. On March 31, 2008, Bell began shooting the [[Mark Steven Johnson]]-written [[Disney]] film ''[[When in Rome (2010 film)|When in Rome]]'' on location in Rome and New York; the film was released in 2010.<ref>{{cite news|last=Fleming |first=Michael |title=Bell to star in 'When in Rome' |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=February 10, 2008 |url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117980628.html?categoryId=13&cs=1 |accessdate=February 11, 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080212182225/http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117980628.html?categoryid=13&cs=1 |archivedate=February 12, 2008 }}</ref> Bell reprised her role as Sarah Marshall for a cameo appearance in the film ''[[Get Him to the Greek]]'', a spin-off [[sequel]] from ''Forgetting Sarah Marshall'', released June 4, 2010.\n\nShe co-starred with singers [[Christina Aguilera]] and [[Cher]] in the musical film ''[[Burlesque (2010 American film)|Burlesque]]'', which was released on Thanksgiving in 2010. Bell had a cameo in the slasher horror film ''[[Scream 4]]'', which was released on April 15, 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ontheredcarpet.com/2010/08/kristen-bell-anna-paquin-to-star-in-scream-4.html?rss=rss-kabc-snippet-7629575 |title=Kristen Bell, Anna Paquin to star in 'Scream 4' |first=Corinne | last=Heller |publisher=OnTheRedCarpet |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100827182434/http://www.ontheredcarpet.com/2010/08/kristen-bell-anna-paquin-to-star-in-scream-4.html?rss=rss-kabc-snippet-7629575 |archivedate=August 27, 2010 |access-date=August 25, 2010 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===2012\u2013present: ''Frozen'' franchise and ''The Good Place''===\nIn 2012, Bell starred in the family drama film ''[[Big Miracle]]''. She has also appeared in the music video for \"Madder Red\" by Brooklyn [[experimental rock]] band [[Yeasayer]]. Bell portrayed [[Mary Magdalene]] in ''The Truth & Life Dramatized Audio New Testament Bible'', a 22-hour, celebrity-voiced, dramatized audio adaptation of the [[New Testament]] that uses the [[Revised Standard Version Catholic Edition|RSV-CE]] translation.\n\n[[File:Kristen Bell at Frozen premiere, El Capitan Theatre.jpg|thumbnail|left|upright|Bell at the premiere of ''[[Frozen (2013 film)|Frozen]]'' in 2013 at the El Capitan Theatre]]\nBell starred as Jeannie van der Hooven, the female lead on the [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] comedy series ''[[House of Lies]]'', which premiered on January 8, 2012. The series ended on June 12, 2016. Bell appeared in a supporting role in the science-fiction comedy ''[[Safety Not Guaranteed]]'' (2012). She starred in the drama film ''[[The Lifeguard]]'', written and directed by [[Liz W. Garcia]], which began filming in July 2012 and was released in August 2013.<ref>{{cite web|first=Mike |last=Fleming |date=July 17, 2012 |title=Kristen Bell to Star in 'The Lifeguard' |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |url=http://www.deadline.com/2012/07/kristen-bell-casting-lifeguard-movie/ |accessdate=July 18, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120718023246/http://www.deadline.com/2012/07/kristen-bell-casting-lifeguard-movie/ |archivedate=July 18, 2012 }}</ref> She also voiced Anna in ''[[Frozen (2013 film)|Frozen]]'', which was released on November 22, 2013. In 2013, for multiple episodes, Bell played Ingrid de Forest, an Eagleton City Councilwoman, on ''[[Parks and Recreation]]''.\n\nOn March 13, 2013, it was confirmed that a ''[[Veronica Mars (film)|Veronica Mars]]'' film would finally be coming to fruition. Bell and series creator [[Rob Thomas (writer)|Rob Thomas]] launched a fundraising campaign to produce the film through [[Kickstarter]] and attained the $2 million goal in less than ten hours.<ref>{{cite web|title='Veronica Mars' movie is a go! 'My mind is blown' says Rob Thomas -- EXCLUSIVE |url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2013/03/13/veronica-mars-movie-is-a-go-kickstarter/ |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |first=Eric |last=Strecker |date=March 13, 2013 |accessdate=March 14, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130315105912/http://insidetv.ew.com/2013/03/13/veronica-mars-movie-is-a-go-kickstarter/ |archivedate=March 15, 2013 }}</ref> The main cast members of the series all reprised their roles in the feature film. Production of the film took place during summer 2013, and it was released theatrically and on video-on-demand on March 14, 2014.<ref name=\"kickstarter\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kickstarter.com/projects/559914737/the-veronica-mars-movie-project?ref=live |title=The Veronica Mars Movie Project |publisher=Kickstarter |accessdate=March 13, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130316043236/http://www.kickstarter.com/projects/559914737/the-veronica-mars-movie-project?ref=live |archivedate=March 16, 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"ew kickstarter\">{{cite web|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2013/03/13/veronica-mars-movie-kristen-bell-kickstarter/ |title='Veronica Mars' movie: Kristen Bell says it's finally happening... if you help -- EXCLUSIVE |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |first=Jeff |last=Jensen |date=March 13, 2013 |accessdate=March 13, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130314232713/http://insidetv.ew.com/2013/03/13/veronica-mars-movie-kristen-bell-kickstarter/ |archivedate=March 14, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIn September 2014, Bell starred with her husband, [[Dax Shepard]], in a commercial for the [[Samsung Galaxy|Samsung Galaxy Tab S]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Galaxy Tab S -- What You Really Need|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=g3Kjj2ca4oQ|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140916033425/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=g3Kjj2ca4oQ|url-status=dead|archive-date=September 16, 2014|website=Youtube.com|publisher=Samsung Mobile USA YouTube|accessdate=December 29, 2014}}</ref> It was so popular (with over 20 million [[YouTube]] views) that they did another for the holiday season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kristen & Dax: Home for the Holidays |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rH-o5JqOXBM |publisher=Samsung Mobile USA YouTube |accessdate=December 29, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141224145133/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rH-o5JqOXBM |archivedate=December 24, 2014 }}</ref> The ad agency [[McKinney (advertising agency)|McKinney]] was behind both.<ref>{{cite web|title=Samsung work page |url=http://mckinney.com/work/clients/samsung |website=Mckinney.com |publisher=McKinney |accessdate=December 29, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141220230543/http://mckinney.com/work/clients/samsung |archivedate=December 20, 2014 }}</ref> In 2016, Bell voiced the [[sloth]] Priscilla in the animated comedy film ''[[Zootopia]]'', and starred as Claire in the comedy film ''[[The Boss (2016 film)|The Boss]]''. Bell starred as Kiki in the 2016 comedy film ''[[Bad Moms]]'', a role she reprised in the 2017 sequel, ''[[A Bad Moms Christmas]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/bad-moms-christmas-trailer-mila-kunis-kathryn-hahn-kristen-bell-watch-1202481014/ |title='Bad Moms Christmas' Trailer: Mila Kunis, Kathryn Hahn, Kristen Bell Stress Out (Watch) |first=Dave |last=McNary |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=June 28, 2017 |accessdate=June 29, 2017 }}</ref> In 2016, Bell began starring as Eleanor Shellstrop in the [[NBC]] comedy series ''[[The Good Place]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2016/01/12/kristen-bell-good-place-nbc-comedy-series-mike-schur-cast/ |title='Kristen Bell, Ted Danson Set to Star in Mike Schur's New NBC Comedy Series' |first=Michael | last=Ausiello |work=Tvline |accessdate=January 12, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160115061006/http://tvline.com/2016/01/12/kristen-bell-good-place-nbc-comedy-series-mike-schur-cast/ |archivedate=January 15, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nAlso in 2017, she appeared in the biographical comedy-drama ''[[The Disaster Artist (film)|The Disaster Artist]]'', the action comedy ''[[Chips (film)|CHiPs]]'' and the comedy ''[[How to Be a Latin Lover]]''. In November 2017, she played a housewife (with Dax Shepard as her husband) preparing for a Christmas party in [[Sia (musician)|Sia]]'s music video for \"[[Everyday Is Christmas (album)|Santa's Coming For Us]]\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Reed|first1=Ryan|title=Watch Sia's 'Santa's Coming for Us' Video With Kristen Bell, J.B. Smoove|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/watch-sias-santas-coming-for-us-video-with-kristen-bell-jb-smoove-w512444|date=November 22, 2017|website=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=December 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, she began hosting the web series ''Momsplaining with Kristen Bell'', with episodes airing on the [[Ellen DeGeneres]] video platform Ellentube. In the series, Bell gives new and expecting mothers tips about motherhood. The title of the series is a pun on the commonly used term \"[[mansplaining]]\".<ref name=\"people.com\">{{cite web|url=http://people.com/babies/kristen-bell-ellen-degeneres-momsplaining-new-series/|title=Kristen Bell Stars in Hilarious New Series About Motherhood \u2014 and Talks Everything from Cracked Nipples to Labor|website=[[People (magazine)|People]] |date=2018-01-25 |accessdate=2020-02-28 |first=Maria |last=Pasquini}}</ref><ref name=\"babble.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.babble.com/entertainment/kristen-bell-momsplaining-video/|title=Kristen Bell's New Web Series \"Momsplaining\" Gets Kids to Open Up in the Most Hilarious Way|date=January 27, 2018|website=Babble.com}}</ref><ref name=\"today.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.today.com/amp/parents/kristen-bell-s-momsplaining-series-shares-parenting-tips-t121858|title=Kristen Bell shares parenting knowledge in new series 'Momsplaining'|website=Today.com |date=2018-01-30 |accessdate=2020-02-28 |first=Allison |last=Slater Tate}}</ref> Bell later had the leading role in the [[Netflix]] comedy-drama film ''[[Like Father]]''. She also voiced the character of Jade Wilson in the animated comedy film ''[[Teen Titans Go! To the Movies]]'' and reprised her voice role as Princess Anna in the animated comedy sequel film ''[[Ralph Breaks the Internet]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://ew.com/movies/2017/07/14/wreck-it-ralph-sequel-star-wars-disney-princesses/|title=Wreck-It Ralph sequel will unite the Disney princesses \u2014 and Star Wars!|last=Breznican|first=Anthony|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=July 14, 2017|accessdate=July 15, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170715013827/http://ew.com/movies/2017/07/14/wreck-it-ralph-sequel-star-wars-disney-princesses/|archivedate=July 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn September 20, 2018, [[Hulu]] confirmed that Bell would reprise her role of Veronica Mars in an 8-episode [[Veronica Mars (season 4)|fourth season]] of the drama series ''Veronica Mars''. The series debuted in July 2019.<ref name=\"ew.com\">{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/tv/2018/09/20/veronica-mars-hulu-details/|title=Veronica Mars reboot officially happening: New details released|date=2018-09-20 |accessdate=2020-02-28 |first=James |last=Hibberd|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]}}</ref> In 2019, she again reprised her role of Princess Anna in the video game, ''[[Kingdom Hearts III]]''<ref name=\"Sep2018Cast\">{{cite press release|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/star-studded-voice-cast-unveiled-for-disney-and-square-enixs-kingdom-hearts-iii-300719139.html|title=Star-Studded Voice Cast Unveiled For Disney And Square Enix's Kingdom Hearts III|publisher=[[Square Enix]]|agency=[[PR Newswire]]|date=September 26, 2018|accessdate=September 26, 2018|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/72iv1pBlT|archivedate=September 26, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and the sequel, ''[[Frozen II]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/trailers/2019/02/13/frozen-2-teaser/|last=Snetiker |first=Marc |date=February 13, 2019|title=Anna and Elsa return in first teaser for Frozen 2|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=June 2, 2019}}</ref> which was released on November 22, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/frozen-2-release-1203017475/|title='Frozen 2' Release Date Moves Up a Week |last1=Rubin |first1=Rebecca |date= November 1, 2018 |accessdate=June 2, 2019 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref> Bell served as host and executive producer on the [[Disney+]] docuseries ''[[Encore! (TV series)|Encore!]]'', which premiered in November 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/disney-non-fiction-slate-supper-club-deal-1203185782/|title=Disney+ Announces Nonfiction Slate, Signs Deal With 'Chef's Table' Producer Supper Club|last=Thorne|first=Will|last2=Thorne|first2=Will|date=2019-04-10|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|access-date=2019-04-12}}</ref> She made her directorial debut with the eighth episode of the fourth season of ''The Good Place''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvline.com/2019/06/05/kristen-bell-the-good-place-season-4-directing/|title=''The Good Place'': Kristen Bell to Make Directorial Debut in Season 4|first=Michael|last=Ausiello|work=TVLine|date=June 5, 2019|accessdate=September 30, 2019}}</ref> The series concluded after its fourth season, airing its final episode in January 2020.<ref name=\"FinalSeason\">{{cite web |url=https://tvline.com/2019/06/07/the-good-place-ending-final-season-4/ |title=The Good Place to End With Season 4 |last=Ausiello |first=Michael |date=June 7, 2019 |website=TVLine |access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBell is set to voice a main character in the [[Apple TV+]] animated musical comedy series ''[[Central Park (TV series)|Central Park]]'', which reunites her with ''Frozen'' co-star [[Josh Gad]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/03/central-park-animated-comedy-series-bobs-burgers-creator-josh-gad-apple-2-season-order-kristen-bell-1202336057/|title=Animated Comedy 'Central Park' From 'Bob's Burgers' Creator & Josh Gad Lands 2-Season Pickup By Apple With Star Cast|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|last2=Andreeva|first2=Nellie|date=2018-03-12|website=Deadline|access-date=2019-04-12}}</ref> She will also voice a character in the animated musical series ''Do, Re, & Mi''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/global/amazon-studios-gaumont-kristen-bell-do-re-mi-1202936643/|title=Amazon Studios Greenlights Gaumont-Kristen Bell Animated Series \u2018Do, Re & Mi\u2019|last=Keslassy|first=Elsa|date=September 11, 2018|website=Variety|access-date=January 17, 2020}}</ref> It was announced that Bell will star alongside [[Leslie Jones (comedian)|Leslie Jones]] as pair of housewives who create a $40 million coupon scam in the comedy film ''Queenpins''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/leslie-jones-kristen-bell-coupon-cartel-saga-queenpins-lands-with-rocket-science-cannes-1202611234/|title=Leslie Jones-Kristen Bell Coupon Caper \u2018Queenpins\u2019 Lands With Rocket Science \u2014 Cannes|last=Wiseman|first=Andreas|date=May 19, 2019|website=Deadline|access-date=January 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==In the media==\nIn 2006 and again in 2013,<ref>{{cite news|title=Kristen Bell and Dax Shephard are PETA's Sexiest Celebrity Vegetarians |url=http://newsfeed.time.com/2013/06/27/kristen-bell-and-dax-shepard-are-petas-sexiest-celebrity-vegetarians/ |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date=2013-06-28 |accessdate=2020-02-28 |first=Olivia B. |last=Waxman |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130630140924/http://newsfeed.time.com/2013/06/27/kristen-bell-and-dax-shepard-are-petas-sexiest-celebrity-vegetarians/ |archivedate=June 30, 2013 }}</ref> Bell was selected \"World's Sexiest [[Vegetarianism|Vegetarian]]\" on [[People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals|PETA]]'s yearly poll.<ref name=\"Veg\"/> She was placed No. 68 on [[Maxim (magazine)|''Maxim'']]'s 2005 \"Hot 100\" list,<ref>{{cite news|title=Maxim Magazine Unveils Their Hot 100 for 2005; Eva Longoria Crowned #1 This Year |publisher=[[Business Wire]] |date=May 10, 2005 |url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0EIN/is_2005_May_10/ai_n13679947 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120526012941/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0EIN/is_2005_May_10/ai_n13679947 |url-status=dead |archive-date=May 26, 2012 |accessdate=January 3, 2008 }}</ref> No. 11 in ''Maxim''{{'}}s 2006 \"Hot 100\" list,<ref>{{cite web|title=Kristen Bell of 2006 Hot 100 on Maxim.com |work=[[Maxim (magazine)|Maxim]] |year=2006 |url=http://www.maximonline.com/slideshows/index.aspx?slideId=1916&imgCollectId=94 |accessdate=January 3, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071104160132/http://www.maximonline.com/slideshows/index.aspx?slideId=1916&imgCollectId=94 |archivedate=November 4, 2007 }}</ref> and No. 46 in ''Maxim''{{'}}s 2007 \"Hot 100\" list in which she was stated to have \"single-handedly saved [[The CW]] from becoming the worst network ever.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Kristen Bell of 2007 Hot 100 on Maxim.com |work=[[Maxim (magazine)|Maxim]] |year=2007 |url=http://www.maximonline.com/slideshows/index.aspx?slideId=3592&imgCollectId=190&src=ad155 |accessdate=January 2, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071226041050/http://www.maximonline.com/slideshows/index.aspx?slideId=3592&imgCollectId=190&src=ad155 |archivedate=December 26, 2007 }}</ref> In 2006, ''Maxim'' also placed Bell at the top of the \"Fall TV's Criminally Sexy Investigators\" List.<ref name=\"Veg\" /> In 2008, she was featured at No. 59 on [[AskMen]]'s Top 99 Women of 2008 List.<ref>{{cite web|title=Top 99 Women of 2008 |publisher=[[Ask Men]] |url=http://www.askmen.com/specials/2008_top_99/kristen-bell-59-1.html |accessdate=February 11, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080227023305/http://www.askmen.com/specials/2008_top_99/kristen-bell-59-1.html |archivedate=February 27, 2008 |df= }}</ref> Reflecting on her admitted popularity with \"geeks\", Bell was voted the fourth-sexiest woman on TV by the staff at [[Wizard (magazine)|''Wizard'' magazine]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wizarduniverse.com/02180825hottvwomen6.html |title=The sexiest women of tv |accessdate=2020-02-28 |date=2008-02-18 |first=Jake |last=Rossen |work=[[Wizard (magazine)|Wizarduniverse.com]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080225202929/http://www.wizarduniverse.com/02180825hottvwomen6.html |archivedate=2008-02-25 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\nBell stated she never thought of herself as womanly because \"I always play and look and act 10 years younger than I am.\" However, she said, \"Something magical happened when I turned 25\u2014I looked in the mirror and was like, 'You might not get carded for an R-rated movie anymore.' Like I didn't have a little stick figure anymore.\"<ref name=\"Complex\">{{cite interview| last= Bell| first= Kristen| interviewer= Tim Leong| title= Kristen Bell in Complex Magazine| work= [[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]| date= January 2008| url= http://www.complexmag.ca/pop-culture/2012/01/kristen-bell-2007-cover-story-gallery| accessdate= January 2, 2008}}</ref> Bell has said that many of her characters are [[tomboy]]s because she was \"not homely enough to play the [[nerd]]y girl and not nearly pretty enough to play the pretty girl\".<ref name=\"Complex\"/>\n[[File:Kristen Bell 2.jpg|alt=Bell leans forward over a table, signing autographs.|thumb|Bell signing autographs at San Francisco's Metreon (June 2006)]]\n\nBell has been associated with the idea that \"[[nerd]]y is the new cool\", and she explained, \"what was previously perceived as nerdy is now viewed as original. What I like about nerdiness, [[geek]]iness, is it doesn't really matter what you're into\u2014it just means you're not a follower.\"<ref name=\"Complex\"/> She has also said, \"I love nerds. [[Comic-Con International|Comic-Con]] junkies are the tastemakers of tomorrow. Isn't that funny? The tables have turned.\"<ref name=\"UGO\"/> Vanessa Juarez of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' commented that Bell's roles on ''Veronica Mars'', ''Heroes'' and as a ''[[Star Wars]]'' fanatic in ''[[Fanboys (film)|Fanboys]]'' have \"solidif[ied] her placement at the center of the geek universe,\" while [[Rodney Rothman]] stated, \"I guess she's cornered the market on losers.\"<ref>{{cite interview|last=Bell |first=Kristen |interviewer=Vanessa Juarez |title=Kristen Bell: Life After 'Mars' |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |year=2007 |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20052938,00.html |accessdate=January 3, 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071230133709/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0%2C%2C20052938%2C00.html |archivedate=December 30, 2007 }}</ref> Bell's work is often compared to [[Sarah Michelle Gellar]]'s portrayal of the [[Buffy Summers|title character]] on the [[cult following|cult]] television series ''[[Buffy the Vampire Slayer]]''.<ref name=\"Bianco-\">{{cite news|first=Robert |last=Bianco |title='Veronica Mars': Intelligent life |work=[[USA Today]] |date=September 21, 2004 |url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/television/reviews/2004-09-21-veronica-mars_x.htm |accessdate=April 9, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070508214351/http://www.usatoday.com/life/television/reviews/2004-09-21-veronica-mars_x.htm |archivedate=May 8, 2007 }}</ref> Frank Scheck of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' stated that Bell was \"arguably the television successor [to Gellar's portrayal of Buffy] when it comes to fighting bad guys.\" Bell is sometimes confused with [[Lauren Conrad]] from ''[[The Hills (TV series)|The Hills]]''. \"Yeah, sometimes fans yell, 'Hey, Lauren' to me, but usually from a distance,\" said Bell.<ref name=\"Pulse\" />\n\nDespite \"new celebrity\" status, Bell claimed that she was not concerned because \"no one ever recognizes me anyway\". She has said that her friend [[Hayden Panettiere]] is more famous than she is and attracts more attention; as Bell explained, \"I hang out with Hayden quite a bit\u2014they never take pictures of me. I just step to the side, and I push myself in front of her when she wants to get out of it, or put her in the car.\"<ref name=\"Complex\" />\n\nBell was a recurring guest on ''[[The Late Late Show with Craig Ferguson]]'', appearing in interviews as well as sketches. On ''The Late Late Show'', she shows a humorous hostility towards [[Craig Ferguson]]'s robot skeleton sidekick [[Geoff Peterson]], claiming that she had wanted to be Ferguson's sidekick on his show and taking it upon herself to cut Peterson down every chance she gets. Both Bell and Peterson appeared with Ferguson during the five ''Late Late Show'' episodes filmed in France.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://watching-tv.ew.com/2011/08/01/craig-ferguson-paris-2/ |title=Craig Ferguson's first show from Paris: A whimsical triumph, a potential classic|first=Ken|last=Tucker|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=August 1, 2011|accessdate=August 28, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2011, it was announced that Bell would be the new face of [[Neutrogena]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.fragrancedirect.co.uk/kristen-bell-is-new-face-of-neutrogena-2584.html |title=Kristen Bell is New Face of Neutrogena |website=Blog.fragrancedirect.co.uk |date=January 26, 2011 |accessdate=July 24, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110812145147/http://blog.fragrancedirect.co.uk/kristen-bell-is-new-face-of-neutrogena-2584.html |archivedate=August 12, 2011 |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Bell was featured on the cover of ''[[Entrepreneur (magazine)|Entrepreneur]]'' magazine's April\u2013May issue. In the article, she discussed her snack bar company, This Saves Lives, which donates its sales to help feed malnourished children around the globe.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Wilkinson |first=Amy |date=Apr 2019 |title= In Good Company |magazine=[[Entrepreneur (magazine)|Entrepreneur]]|location= |publisher= |access-date= }}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, Bell and [[Idina Menzel]], who play sisters in [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney's]] [[Frozen (franchise)|''Frozen'' franchise]], received neighboring stars\u2014Bell's was the 2681<sup>st</sup> and Menzel's was the 2682<sup>nd</sup>\u2014on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]].<ref>{{cite AV media |date=November 8, 2019 |title='Sisters' Menzel and Bell celebrate Walk of Fame news |medium=[[YouTube]] |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XLcgesPFxgk |publisher=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlive.com/news/2019/11/michigan-actress-kristen-bell-gets-star-on-hollywood-walk-of-fame.html |title=Michigan actress Kristen Bell gets star on Hollywood Walk of Fame |website=mlive.com |date=2019-11-20 |accessdate=2020-02-28 |first=Brandon |last=Champion}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\n===Relationships and family===\nIn 2007, Bell ended a five-year relationship with former fianc\u00e9 Kevin Mann.<ref>{{cite web|title='When in Rome' stars Kristen Bell and Dax Shepard are engaged! |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Tronc]]|location=Los Angeles, California|first=Matt|last=Donnelly |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/gossip/2010/02/kristen-bell-dax-shepard-engaged-.html |date=February 1, 2010 |access-date=April 23, 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140506105735/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/gossip/2010/02/kristen-bell-dax-shepard-engaged-.html |archive-date=May 6, 2014 }}</ref> She later told ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]'' magazine that dating \"makes me want to vomit. And not out of grossness\u2014OK, a little bit out of grossness, but just nerves... I've always been a serial [[Monogamy|monogamist]].\"<ref name=\"Complex\" />\n\nIn late 2007, Bell began dating actor [[Dax Shepard]], who is also from Metro Detroit. The couple announced their engagement in January 2010.<ref>{{cite web|title=Exclusive: Kristen Bell Is Engaged to Dax Shepard! |work=[[Us Weekly|Us Magazine]] |date=January 31, 2010 |url=http://www.usmagazine.com/celebritynews/news/kristen-bell-is-engaged-to-dax-shepherd-2010311 |access-date=February 1, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100203070901/http://www.usmagazine.com/celebritynews/news/kristen-bell-is-engaged-to-dax-shepherd-2010311 |archivedate=February 3, 2010 }}</ref> They decided to delay marriage until the state of California passed legislation legalizing [[same-sex marriage]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.celebuzz.com/2012-08-14/hit-run-couple-kristen-bell-and-dax-shepard-on-playing-onscreen-lovers-they-do-mirror-a-portion-of-us/ |title='Hit & Run' Couple Kristen Bell and Dax Shepard Won't Marry Until Same-Sex Marriage is Legal in California |publisher=Celebuzz |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141015171700/http://www.celebuzz.com/2012-08-14/hit-run-couple-kristen-bell-and-dax-shepard-on-playing-onscreen-lovers-they-do-mirror-a-portion-of-us/ |archivedate=October 15, 2014 }}</ref> They co-starred in the 2010 film ''[[When in Rome (2010 film)|When in Rome]]'', the 2012 film ''[[Hit and Run (2012 film)|Hit and Run]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1692375/kristen-bell-dax-shepard-hit-and-run-directorial-debut.jhtml |title=Kristen Bell Admires 'Cute' Dax Shepard On 'Hit & Run' Set |publisher=MTV News |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120825172004/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1692375/kristen-bell-dax-shepard-hit-and-run-directorial-debut.jhtml |archivedate=2012-08-25 |date=2012-08-22 |first=Kara |last=Warner}}</ref> and the 2017 film ''[[CHiPs (film)|CHiPs]]''. After section 3 of the [[Defense of Marriage Act]] was ruled unconstitutional by the [[U.S. Supreme Court|Supreme Court]] on June 26, 2013, Bell asked Shepard to marry her through Twitter,<ref name=Twitter-KristenProp-2013>{{cite tweet|number=349901645343232000?s=21|title=.@daxshepard1 will you marry me? Xo #marriageequality #loveislove\"|first=Kristen|last=Bell|user=IMKristenBell|date=June 26, 2013|accessdate=June 26, 2013}}</ref> which he accepted.<ref name=DaxProp-2013>{{cite tweet|title=@IMKristenBell Fuck Yes!!!!!!!!!!!|first=Dax|last=Shepard|user=daxshepard1|date=June 26, 2013|number=349921536683147264|accessdate=June 26, 2013}}</ref> They were married at the [[Beverly Hills, California|Beverly Hills]] County Clerk's Office on October 16, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kristen Bell, Dax Shepard Get Married in \"No Frills\" Wedding at County Clerk's Office |work=[[Us Weekly]] |date=October 17, 2013 |url=http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/kristen-bell-dax-shepard-get-married-in-no-frills-ceremony-at-county-clerks-office-report-20131710 |accessdate=October 19, 2013 |first=Justin |last=Ravitz |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131018135013/http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/kristen-bell-dax-shepard-get-married-in-no-frills-ceremony-at-county-clerks-office-report-20131710 |archivedate=October 18, 2013 }}</ref> They have two daughters, the first born in 2013<ref>{{cite web |title=Dax Shepard and Kristen Bell Welcome Daughter Lincoln |work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |date=March 28, 2013 |url=https://people.com/parents/kristen-bell-dax-shepard-welcome-daughter-lincoln/|accessdate=March 29, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130328232909/http://celebritybabies.people.com/2013/03/28/kristen-bell-dax-shepard-welcome-daughter-lincoln/ |archivedate=March 28, 2013}}</ref> and the second born in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/parents/kristen-bell-dax-shepard-welcome-daughter-delta/|title=Dax Shepard and Kristen Bell Welcome Daughter Delta |work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |date=December 19, 2014 |accessdate=December 19, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141220065332/http://celebritybabies.people.com/2014/12/19/kristen-bell-dax-shepard-welcome-daughter-delta/ |archivedate=December 20, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n===Beliefs, interests and charity work===\n[[File:Kristen Bell 2012.jpg|thumb|Bell with the Dancing Merengue Dog at the [[2012 Bonnaroo Music Festival]]]]\nAt age 11, Bell became a [[vegetarianism|vegetarian]].<ref name=\"Veg\">{{cite web|title=Kristen Didn't Like Kristen |website=Stylecritics.com |date=October 25, 2007 |url=http://www.stylecritics.com/celebrities/2007/10/25/kristen-didnt-like-kristen/ |accessdate=January 4, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080330020948/http://www.stylecritics.com/celebrities/2007/10/25/kristen-didnt-like-kristen/ |archivedate=March 30, 2008 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> In an interview with PETA, Bell stated, \"I have always been an animal lover. I had a hard time disassociating the animals I cuddled with\u2014dogs and cats, for example\u2014from the animals on my plate, and I never really cared for the taste of meat. I always loved my [[Brussels sprout]]s!\"<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|title=Pop Icon Prince and Veronica Mars' Kristen Bell Voted 'World's Sexiest Vegetarians' |publisher=[[People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals|PETA]] |url=http://www.goveg.com/feat/sexiestveg2006/ |accessdate=December 6, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071201091729/http://www.goveg.com/feat/sexiestveg2006/ |archivedate=December 1, 2007 }}</ref> By 2012 Bell had become [[veganism|vegan]] with her husband after watching the documentary ''[[Forks Over Knives]]''.<ref name=\"BellDax\">[http://www.womenshealthmag.com/life/kristen-bell-vegan-food/ \"Kristen in the Kitchen\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120721213003/http://www.womenshealthmag.com/life/kristen-bell-vegan-food |date=July 21, 2012 }}, ''Women's Health'', March 8, 2012.</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/06/27/peta-sexiest-vegetarian-2013-kristen-bell-dax-shephard_n_3511411.html |title=PETA Sexiest Vegetarian Celebrities 2013: Kristen Bell, Dax Shephard Share Feel-Good Honors |work=[[The Huffington Post]] |date=June 27, 2013 |accessdate=July 11, 2013 |quote=A vegetarian for many years, Bell eventually decided to go vegan along with [boyfriend Dax] Shepard, who \"converted\" last January after watching the documentary \"Forks Over Knives,\" according to Playboy. |first=Meredith |last=Bennett-Smith |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130702074643/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/06/27/peta-sexiest-vegetarian-2013-kristen-bell-dax-shephard_n_3511411.html |archivedate=July 2, 2013 }}</ref> During her first pregnancy, she returned to eating dairy and eggs, however.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=September 1, 2018|url=https://www.today.com/food/why-kristen-bell-stopped-vegan-diet-go-vegetarian-t117396|title=Why Kristen Bell ditched a strict vegan diet after her first pregnancy|first=Katie |last=Jackson|date=October 17, 2017|website=[[Today.com]]|location=Jamaica|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171018052054/https://www.today.com/food/why-kristen-bell-stopped-vegan-diet-go-vegetarian-t117396|archivedate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> During her time in Michigan, Bell fostered animals from the [[Michigan Humane Society]], and she now supports the San Diego-based [[Helen Woodward Animal Center]]. Bell often attends fundraisers for the [[American Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals]] and other non-profit organizations dedicated to protecting animals. She has had several dogs, including a [[Welsh Corgi]]-[[Chow Chow]] mix named Lola, a Welsh Corgi-[[Chihuahua (dog)|Chihuahua]] mix named Shakey, and a black [[Labrador Retriever]] named Sadie, who was 11 years old when she was rescued from [[Hurricane Katrina]] and adopted by Bell in 2005.<ref name=\"Mars\"/><ref>{{cite interview| last= Bell| first= Kristen| interviewer= Michigan Humane Society| title= Celebrity Chat with Kristen Bell| work= [[Michigan Humane Society]]| year= 2007| url= http://www.michiganhumane.org/site/News2?page=NewsArticle&id=8333| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20080123205715/http://www.michiganhumane.org/site/News2?page=NewsArticle&id=8333| url-status=dead| archive-date= January 23, 2008| accessdate= January 4, 2008}}</ref>\n\nBell has stated she is [[non-religious]] and identifies as a [[humanist]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/movies/kristen-bell-opens-up-religious-mom-turbulent-past/|title=Kristen Bell Opens Up About Her Religious Mom: 'We Have Had a Lot of Turbulence in the Past'|website=[[People (magazine)|People]]|accessdate=2020-02-28 |date=2018-09-20 |first=Alexia |last=Fernandez}}</ref> Bell and other ''Veronica Mars'' cast members, including [[Ryan Hansen]], are involved with the charity [[Invisible Children, Inc.]] The goal of the organization is to create awareness of the plight of [[Northern Uganda]]ns who are caught in the midst of a [[civil war]] between the government and [[Joseph Kony]]'s [[Lord's Resistance Army]].<ref name=\"LoVe\">{{cite interview|last=Bell |first=Kristen |interviewer=Angel Cohn |title=Veronica Mars' Kristen Bell Talks of Laughs and LoVe |work=[[TV Guide]] |date=February 27, 2007 |url=http://www.tv.com/tracking/viewer.html?tid=99405&ref_id=180276&ref_type=104 |accessdate=January 3, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081216091523/http://www.tv.com/tracking/viewer.html?tid=99405&ref_id=180276&ref_type=104 |archivedate=December 16, 2008 |df= }}</ref> Bell has also done a public service announcement for [[Do Something]]'s Healthy Living Campaign.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=K8oBvNvg7Gc&feature=channel_page.html |title=Kristen Bell Talks About Healthy Living |accessdate=October 2, 2007 |publisher=[[Do Something]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140906162435/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=K8oBvNvg7Gc&feature=channel_page.html |archivedate=September 6, 2014 }}</ref> In 2014, Bell launched a [[Prizeo]] campaign offering fans a chance to win a date with her in return for donating to Invisible Children, Inc.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/07/03/kristen-bell-prizeo-date_n_3541988.html |title=Kristen Bell Offering Up Date for Charity |first1=Nader|last1=Salass |date=July 3, 2013 |website=[[The Huffington Post]]|location=New York City|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151015111621/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/07/03/kristen-bell-prizeo-date_n_3541988.html |archivedate=October 15, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nBell supported and campaigned for [[Barack Obama]] during the [[2008 United States presidential election]]. Along with [[Rashida Jones]], she visited college campuses in [[Missouri]] to discuss the candidates and encourage voter registration.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.therolladailynews.com/news/x1272959530/State-urges-voter-registration |title=State urges voter registration |last=Kotyk |first=KC |date=October 4, 2008 |work=The Rolla Daily News |accessdate=June 26, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081119080220/http://www.therolladailynews.com/news/x1272959530/State-urges-voter-registration |archivedate=November 19, 2008  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Battle for votes goes to Springfield streets|last=Livengood|first=Chad |date=October 5, 2008|work=Springfield News-Leader}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Schueler |first=John |url=http://my.barackobama.com/page/community/post/MOblog/gGxGx5 |title=Hollywood Starlets Challenge Rolla Students to Make their Voices Heard |website=My.barackobama.com |date=October 3, 2008 |accessdate=July 24, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120531125922/https://my.barackobama.com/page/community/post/MOblog/gGxGx5 |archivedate=May 31, 2012 }}</ref> Bell showed support for the [[Writers Guild of America]] in the [[2007\u201308 Writers Guild of America strike|writers' strike]], appearing in the picket lines in December 2007, stating, \"the writers are just looking for some fairness.\"<ref>{{cite interview|last=Bell |first=Kristen |interviewer=Eric Goldman |title=Heroes: Kristen Bell on the Strike |work=[[IGN]] |date=December 11, 2007 |url=http://tv.ign.com/articles/840/840914p1.html |accessdate=January 3, 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071215031544/http://tv.ign.com/articles/840/840914p1.html |archivedate=December 15, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nBell and her husband Dax Shepard are staunchly pro-vaccination.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/kristen-bell-demands-friends-get-772242|title=Kristen Bell Demands Friends Get Whooping Cough Vaccination Before Holding Her Baby|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=2020-02-28 |date=2015-02-14 |first=Chris |last=Gardner}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/kristen-bell-and-dax-shepard-criticized-for-supporting-vaccines-you-popped-out-a-kid-not-a-ph-d-220017921.html|title=Kristen Bell and Dax Shepard criticized for supporting vaccines: 'You popped out a kid, not a PhD'|work=Yahoo |accessdate=2020-02-28 |date=2019-06-22 |first=Raechal |last=Stewart}}</ref>\n\n===Mental health===\nIn May 2016, Bell stated that she has struggled with and received treatment for [[depression (mood)|depression]] and [[Anxiety disorder|anxiety]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mYUQ_nlZgWE|title=Kristen Bell Explains There Is No Shame In Feeling Anxiety & Depression|last=theoffcamerashow|date=April 6, 2016|publisher=|access-date=May 5, 2019|via=YouTube}}</ref> She said, \"It's important for me to be candid about this so people in a similar situation can realize that they are not worthless and that they do have something to offer.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bell |first1=Kristen |title=Kristen Bell Shares Struggles With Depression and Anxiety |url=http://motto.time.com/4352130/kristen-bell-frozen-depression-anxiety/ |website=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |access-date=June 2, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160602040600/http://motto.time.com/4352130/kristen-bell-frozen-depression-anxiety/ |archive-date=June 2, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n===Entrepreneurship===\nIn 2019, Bell and her husband founded the company Hello Bello, a plant-based baby care product line. The product line focuses on creating environmentally friendly and affordable products. The company partnered exclusively with [[Walmart]] and the line is sold in all locations, as well as online.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hellobello.com/|title=Hello Bello - Natural, Affordable, Premium For All|author=|date=|website=Hello Bello|access-date=May 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n<!-- Please note: do NOT use \"rowspans\" per WP:FILMOGRAPHY -->\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|1998\n|''[[Polish Wedding]]''\n|Teenage girl\n|Uncredited<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.moviefone.com/2008/04/15/stars-in-rewind-kristen-bell-has-american-dreams-and-polish-weddi/|title=Stars in Rewind: Kristen Bell Has American Dreams & Polish Weddings|website=MovieFone.com|first=Monika|last=Bartyzel|date=April 15, 2008|accessdate=April 10, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170622044505/https://www.moviefone.com/2008/04/15/stars-in-rewind-kristen-bell-has-american-dreams-and-polish-weddi/|archive-date=June 22, 2017|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n|2001\n|''[[Pootie Tang]]''\n|Record executive's daughter\n|\n|-\n|2002\n|''People Are Dead''\n|Angela's friend #1\n|\n|-\n|2003\n|''[[The Cat Returns]]''\n|Hiromi (voice)\n|Englis